PART I: THE VISUAL IDENTITY — TEXTILE NOUVEAU IN ABSOLUTE DEPTH

1.1 The Threadweave Engine — Expanded

The Threadweave Engine is not merely a renderer; it is a full simulation of textile physics at the microscopic level. It operates on three parallel layers:

1.1.1 The Macro Structure Layer

This defines the 3D geometry of objects using a smooth, organic mesh. All edges are rounded with a minimum radius of 2cm, simulating the natural curve of stuffed fabric. The mesh is dynamically subdivided based on camera proximity to maintain silky silhouettes without visible polygon angles. The engine uses a proprietary algorithm called Curvilinear Surface Weaving (CSW) that ensures every surface, even at a distance, appears to have a directional weave pattern projected onto it, eliminating the "flat texture" look.

1.1.2 The Fiber Dynamics Layer

This is the heart of the engine. Every surface material is defined by a Fiber Array — a dense, 3D distribution of virtual fibers, each fiber being a tiny cylinder with properties:

· Cross-section shape: Circular (wool), triangular (silk, for luster), kidney (cotton), flat (ribbon for metallic).
· Length and curl: Wool fibers have a 3D crimp defined by a sine wave with a specific amplitude and frequency; silk fibers are straight; cotton fibers have a gentle twist.
· Inter-fiber friction: Dictated by the fiber's surface roughness (e.g., wool scales cause high friction, silk has very low).
· Ply and twist: The fiber array itself is twisted into yarns (a group of fibers twisted together) and those yarns are then knitted, woven, or felted. The engine simulates the torsional energy of these twists, so when a woven fabric is cut, the edge slightly curls based on the weave's internal tension.

When the player or an object interacts with a surface, the fibers are displaced in real time. Stepping on a plush velvet carpet crushes the pile; the fibers slowly rebound over 15–45 seconds depending on material resilience. A heavy chest placed on a silk cushion creates a permanent depression until moved. This is all calculated on the GPU using a compute shader, handling millions of individual fiber interactions.

1.1.3 The Threadlight & Subsurface Layer

All materials have a Lumen Inclusion Density property. Tiny particles of glowing Lumen Thread are embedded within the fiber array. When light (from Threadlight sources) hits a material, it enters the surface and scatters among the fibers, picking up their color, before exiting. This gives all materials a soft, glowing translucency. The effect is most dramatic in silk (where light travels along the smooth fibers) and thinnest in dense wool. The Threadlight simulation also includes a Weave-Phosphorescence: after exposure to bright Threadlight, some materials (like Frostspun Lace or Astral Silk) glow faintly for several minutes in the dark, slowly dimming.

