1.3 The Palette of the Cosmos — The Dyer's Art

The game's color system is based entirely on natural dyeing, expanded with magical equivalents.

1.3.1 The Dyer's Notebook

This is a dedicated section of the Pattern Book, a fabric swatch book with actual miniature woven patches pinned to the pages. Each discovered dye source is documented: the plant/mineral, its processing method, and the resulting color on wool, silk, and cotton (as these fibers take dye differently). The player can mix dyes in a Dye Vat, a large, animated gourd with a simmering liquid surface. The interface allows precise measurement by weight (grams of dried root, liters of water, grams of mordant) to replicate colors exactly.

1.3.2 Dye Sources

· Madder Root (Elysian): Produces a range of warm reds to oranges depending on mordant. Alum = bright coral; iron = brick red.
· Indigo (Verdant Tapestry): A vat dye that requires fermentation. Fabric emerges green and oxidizes to deep blue in the air — a beautiful, slow animation.
· Cochineal (Emberweave, from tiny scale insects living on cacti): Brilliant scarlet to crimson. Extremely valuable.
· Weld (Elysian): Bright, clear yellow.
· Logwood (Unspooled Deep, from sunken trees): Deep purples and blacks with iron.
· Turmeric (Verdant): Golden yellow, but fades quickly in Threadlight unless fixed.
· Osage Orange (Golden Braid): Vibrant gold-yellow.
· Woad (Frostspun): A pale, icy blue, the traditional dye of the Frost Sprites.
· Sea Snail Mucus (Sundered Shores): Rare, produces Tyrian purple.
· Glowworm Paste (Astral Silk): Adds a permanent, faint bioluminescence to any dye mix, creating colors that glow in the dark.

1.3.3 Dyeing Techniques

· Immersion Dyeing: Dipping the whole item. The game simulates dye penetration based on fiber density.
· Tie-Dye: Using thread wraps to create resist patterns. The player can paint the wraps directly onto the 3D model.
· Shibori: Complex stitched resists, creating precise, repeating patterns (woodgrain, spiderweb). An entire puzzle mini-game is centered on learning Shibori patterns from Glimmer Moths.
· Ombré/ Dip-Dye: Slowly raising or lowering the item from the vat. The game calculates the gradient based on immersion time and speed.
· Painting: Using a brush with thickened dye paste on silk, which spreads slightly, mimicking watercolor.

