· Burst Snag: A pulsating, bulging knot. When the Weaver is within 2 metres, it detonates into 4 smaller Thorn Snags that spread to adjacent lanes. The safe play is to dash through it just before it bursts, destroying the whole cluster.
· Memory Snag: A rare snag that looks like a gray face. When touched, it doesn't crash you but replays a 3-second loop of a tragic memory, causing screen tearing and a temporary Lumen drain (10% of current orbs). It can only be destroyed by a Needle Dash.

3.2.2 Loom Sentinels Expanded — Mini-Bosses of the Braidway

· Needle Knight: 3 metres tall, needle sword. It stands in the center lane and thrusts its sword into the left or right lane, then sweeps. The tell is the direction its head (a pincushion) turns. Dodge the thrust by being in the opposite lane; jump the sweep. A perfectly timed slide under the sweep gives a "Duck and Weave" bonus.
· Shuttle Mage: Floats, shoots three shuttle-shaped projectiles down the lanes in sequence. The projectiles are slow but home slightly. You must weave between them. Dashing into the mage destroys it.
· Bobbin Brute: Giant, cylindrical body made of wound grey yarn. It slams the Braidway, creating a shockwave that rolls down all lanes. The shockwave must be jumped over. After the slam, the brute is stunned for 2 seconds, during which you can dash into it to destroy it.

3.2.3 Unravelling Phenomena — Environmental Hazards

· Static Sink: A dark, humming patch on the Braidway that covers two lanes. Stepping on it slows you and drains 5 Lumen per second. It's a pothole that you must lane-switch or jump over.
· Threadquake: The screen shakes, and for 5 seconds, obstacles randomly spawn and despawn, shifting lanes rapidly. There's no safe lane; you must react instantly.
· Void Tendril: A massive, smoky tentacle that rises from beneath the Braidway. It sweeps across all lanes in a wave pattern. You must jump over it. It has a "wind-up" animation (the ribbon fraying at the edges) giving a 1-second warning.

3.3 Power-Up Deep Customisation & Crafting

Power-ups are not just pick-ups; they are temporary enhancements that can be permanently upgraded and customized.

3.3.1 The Spindlecraft Table

This is a crafting station in the Hearth specifically for power-ups. You don't craft the power-ups themselves; you craft Power-Up Boosters, which are then socketed into the power-up's "pattern" at the Heartstone.

· Duration Extender: +2/+5/+8 seconds. Crafted with Silk and Lumen.
· Effect Intensifier: Level 1: Shield absorbs 2 hits. Level 2: Trail is 50% wider. Level 3: Surge slows time by an additional 20%. Crafted with rare metals.
· Synergy Socket: A special, difficult-to-craft item that allows you to combine two power-ups into a single hoop. The hoop appears as a double-ring. E.g., combining Shuttle Shield and Tapestry Trail creates a Trail Shield: a shield that also leaves a trail, so you're collecting orbs while protected.
· Aesthetic Overlay: Craft a "dye pack" that permanently changes the visual of a specific power-up for you. Make your Jetpack wings look like flaming phoenix feathers, or your magnet field appear as swirling autumn leaves.

3.3.2 New Power-Ups — Full Profiles

· Mirror Image: Creates two translucent, silver-thread clones in the adjacent lanes. For 12 seconds, they mimic your movements (lane-switching, jumping, sliding) with a 0.5-second delay. They collect orbs and can destroy obstacles. The visual is a beautiful, triple-exposure effect.
· Thread Void: The Weaver throws a black, tangled ball forward. It sticks to the first obstacle hit, then expands into a 3-metre radius void that sucks in all nearby obstacles and Wisps, converting them into Lumen Orbs. It lasts 5 seconds. The sound is a deep, resonant pluck.
· Temporal Spool: The Braidway around the Weaver (15 metres ahead) freezes entirely. All obstacles, wisps, and even falling Lumen Orbs become still, covered in a thin layer of ice-lace. The effect lasts 6 seconds. You can walk through frozen obstacles, and they shatter after the effect ends, dropping bonus orbs.
· Loom's Favor: For 20 seconds, any near-miss (within 30cm of an obstacle) triggers a burst of 10 Lumen Orbs and refills half a dash charge. The Weaver's eyes glow intensely, and the sound of a cheering crowd of Spindlekin is heard softly.

3.4 Co-op Running: Tandem Weave — Detailed Systems

3.4.1 Connection & Syncing

Two players on any platform can run together. The Braidway widens to 7 lanes. Player 1 occupies lanes 1–3 by default, Player 2 occupies 5–7; lane 4 is the neutral center. Both players share a single, slightly zoomed-out camera. The game uses a proprietary netcode that predicts player movement to eliminate desync, making it feel like local co-op.

3.4.2 Shared Mechanics

· Harmony Multiplier: Starts at x1. Increases by +0.1 for every near-miss performed simultaneously by both players, and +0.5 for perfectly synchronized dodges. Resets when one player takes a hit.
· Revive Mechanic: If one player crashes, they become a floating, ghostly spool of thread at the crash point. The surviving player has 5 seconds to dash through the spool to revive them, costing one of their own dash charges. The revived player returns with 1-second invincibility. If not revived in time, the run ends for both.
· Tandem Power-Ups: Special power-ups appear only in co-op: Link Stitch (a glowing tether connects both players; if they stay linked for 10 seconds, a massive Lumen burst is awarded), Swap Surge (instantly swap lanes with your partner), and Combined Shuttle (a single, massive shuttle shield that protects both).

