PART VI: BUILDING & CREATION — THE ART OF THE STITCH, ULTIMATE TOOLKIT

6.1 Stitch Tiles — The Smart Tile System Perfected

Stitch Tiles are the foundation of building. The Placement Hologram is a soft, glowing grid of warp and weft threads that overlay the world. Tiles come in basic shapes: Cube, Slab, Stair, Pillar, Arch, Dome, and Spike, but the Morphing tool lets you drag any face, edge, or vertex to reshape it into any organic form, like sculpting clay.

6.1.1 Seam System

When two tiles of different materials meet, a seam is generated. The default seam is a simple whipstitch. Using the Seam Ripper tool, you can change the seam type per edge:

· Flat-Felled: A sturdy, folded seam. Good for structural walls. Reduces weather penetration.
· French Seam: An enclosed, tidy seam. Good for fine furniture. Increases beauty score.
· Piped Seam: A decorative cord is sewn in. Adds a trim color option.
· Lace Overlay: The seam is bridged by a strip of lace. Lets light through.
· Frayed Edge: Intentionally unravelled. Used for ruins or a punk aesthetic.
· Lighting Seam: Embeds a Lumen Thread, making the seam itself a light source.

6.1.2 Tile Properties & Simulation

Each tile material has physical properties that affect the game world:

· Acoustic Absorption (0–100): A wool wall absorbs sound, making a room quiet; a silk wall reflects it, causing echo. This is linked to the music system: a room with high absorption plays a muffled version of the soundtrack.
· Thermal Resistance: The ability to insulate. A wool house in Frostspun stays warmer. A silk tent in Emberweave stays cooler.
· Translucency: A silk organza wall lets diffuse light through; a velvet wall blocks all light. This creates dynamic interior lighting based on the sun's position.
· Tensile Softness: A trampoline-like silk floor vs. a hard felt floor, affecting jump height and footstep sound.

6.2 Furniture Weaving — The Micro-Loom Interface

The Pattern Bench is a full 3D modeling environment disguised as a loom. When crafting furniture, you enter a detailed view where the piece is constructed step-by-step.

6.2.1 Crafting a Simple Chair (Example Process)

1. Frame Selection: Choose a wooden frame (Curved Velvet-Wood). You see a holographic outline.
2. Warping: String the warp threads for the seat (choose Silk Charmeuse in Emerald). You pull the shuttle back and forth, and the seat weaves in real time.
3. Weft Patterning: Change the weft color for stripes. The interface shows a mini pattern graph.
4. Tufting: For an upholstered look, you select the tufting tool and click points on the seat surface. The game pulls the fabric into a buttoned divot, and you can insert a button (choose from your button collection).
5. Finishing: Add piping around the edges (Gold Lamé) and apply a stain to the wood (Indigo + Walnut dye).
6. Final Product: The chair is added to your inventory as a placed item. You can save the exact "recipe" as a blueprint for mass production.

6.2.2 Lighting

Lighting is created by combining a Lumen Orb (or a cluster) with a Shade made of any material. A Lumen Orb inside a Frostspun Lace shade casts intricate shadow patterns. Inside a Golden Brocade shade, it casts a warm, regal glow. The orb's color can be set to any dye color. You can also create Thread Candles: a slow-burning Lumen-infused wick in a wax-like fat (from the Nap Sheep), which flickers realistically and can be scented with flower petals to provide a minor buff in the room.

6.3 Loom Servitors — Artificial Companions

A Loom Servitor is crafted from a special Animated Yarn (a rare thread from the Unspooled Deep, imbued with a Leviathan's memory of movement). The crafting process involves knitting the body over a frame on a Servitor Loom. The shape you knit determines its function:

· Quadruped Base: Good for carrying items, acts as a mobile chest.
· Biped Base: Can manipulate tools, perform crafting tasks, and fight.
· Arachnid Base: Climbs walls, useful for building in high places.

6.3.1 Weave-Command Programming

Servitors are programmed using a visual scripting language called the Weave-Command. It's represented as a piece of woven cloth, where the warp threads are "sensors" (if it's dawn, if chest is full) and the weft threads are "actions" (move to location, harvest, attack). The player weaves these threads together on a small loom interface. Complex commands can be saved as "Script Swatches." For example, a "Farmer Servitor" script: [Dawn] -> [Move to field A] -> [Harvest all ripe] -> [Deposit in Barn] -> [If field A empty, move to field B].

Servitors can be upgraded with better eyes (gem buttons for longer sight), stronger muscles (Ember Silk for more carry weight), and a "Loom-Spark" brain for conditional logic. They run on Lumen, which they draw from a charging station you must build.

---

PART VII: COMBAT, DUNGEONS & THE UNRAVELLING — THE THREAD OF CONFLICT

7.1 Combat System Refined — Thread Dance

Combat is a dance of distance and thread. The Weaver's primary weapon is the Needle Rapier, a rapier-thin, 1-metre needle. It has a light attack (quick, three-hit combo), a heavy attack (a lunge that can break armor), and a charged attack (a spinning sweep). The Dash has generous i-frames and leaves a short-lived thread image that can distract enemies. The Cloak Parry is a timed twirl that deflects projectiles and staggers melee attackers if perfectly timed.

7.1.1 New Weapons

· The Shuttle Sling: A ranged weapon that flings spools of thread. The spools can be elemental (fire spool from Emberweave, ice spool from Frostspun).
· The Tapestry Needles: Dual-wielded, shorter needles for a fast, flurry-based combat style.
· The Loom Anchor: A heavy, magical flail that creates a static field, slowing Unravelled within it.

7.1.2 Unravelled Bestiary — Complete

· Skittering Snags: Weak, fast, often in packs.
· Wraith Stitches: Phasing, ranged attacks. Vulnerable after attacking.
· Gnarled Sentinels: Heavy, slow, with a charge attack and a ground slam.
· Threadripper: A massive, four-legged beast made of torn tapestry. It breathes a cone of static. Its weak point is a golden thread on its belly; you must slide under it.
· The Silence: A rare, incorporeal Unravelled that doesn't damage you but drains your Lumen. It's visible only in the reflection of a polished button, requiring a button-shield item to see and fight it.
· Boss: The Gnar: A multi-phase battle. Phase 1: thrashing limbs. Phase 2: the arena darkens, the Gnar sinks into the floor, and you must trace the outline of its core by pulling glowing threads in a dark room. Phase 3: the core is exposed, a rhythm-based re-stitching mini-game appears to purify it. Success yields a Heartstone Fragment and the boss's "Essence Thread," a unique material for crafting a boss-weapon.

7.2 Tangled Ruins — Procedural Labyrinths

Ruins are generated by the Knot Simulation Algorithm, which simulates tying a massive ball of yarn, then hollowing out tunnels. The walls are animated, showing slowly shifting threads. There are Puzzle Rooms, Trap Corridors (where the floor un-weaves), and Treasure Vaults. The deeper you go, the more likely you are to find a Memory Tapestry Shard. Each ruin has a hidden Loom Chamber where the boss resides, and the door requires solving a weaving puzzle (e.g., thread a specific pattern using the warp threads on a small loom).

