PART XI: THE ECONOMY OF LUMEN AND THREAD — RESOURCE FLOW

11.1 Lumen Orbs — The Lifeblood

Lumen Orbs are not a set value; their quality varies. In a Spindle Run, orbs found in the later, faster sections are Brighter Orbs, worth 10% more. Orbs found during a Loom Surge are Surge Orbs, shimmering with extra light and worth double. You can "save" orbs by depositing them at a Heartstone immediately after a run; if you die again in a dungeon before depositing, you lose half of your unbanked orbs.

11.2 Thread Spools — Material Tiers & Rarity

Thread Spools come in Graded Qualities: Frayed, Common, Fine, Exquisite, and Perfect. The quality affects the item crafted. A Perfect Ember Silk makes a tool with extra durability. Quality is increased by using better tools, having high friendship with the producing Spindlekin, or during certain seasonal events. The highest quality items require a "Perfect" grade spool, which often comes from a perfect performance in a Spindle Run challenge or a boss drop.

11.3 Trading with Spindlekin — The Bartering Dance

Trading is a full interaction. When you approach a merchant, they present their current wares on a woven mat. You select what you want and place your offer on your side of the mat. The merchant considers it (an animation of scratching their chin with a needle). Their response is based on the item's value, their current need, and your friendship. You can then counter-offer, add a gift, or use a special "Haggle" emote (learned from the Glimmer Moths) that has a chance to improve the deal but can sometimes offend them if used too much. A successful trade increases friendship. A merchant's stock rotates daily and is influenced by the realm's current status (a Frostspun merchant sells more cold-weather gear in winter).

---

PART XII: ACCESSIBILITY, COMFORT, AND THE ENDLESS WEAVE

12.1 The Tapestry of Deeds — Your Living Legacy

Every major and minor achievement is recorded. The Tapestry of Deeds is not just a list; it's a physical, woven mural on your Hearth island that grows over time. You can interact with any part of it to zoom in and see the embroidered scene, the date (in the Great Loom Calendar), and a short note. Visiting friends can view your Tapestry and leave a small, anonymous "Guest Stitch" (a single cross-stitch) on a dedicated border.

12.2 Endgame: The Eternal Loom

There is no end. After the Loom's Edge, you continue to expand your cosmology. The goal becomes perfection: unlocking every recipe, reaching Weaver Rank 100, befriending every Spindlekin, and completing every event. The "Final Task" is a community-driven meta-goal: to collectively weave the "Impossible Tapestry," a massive, collaborative art project where every player can contribute one stitch, stored on a central server. It is a never-ending piece of art that represents the entire player base.

12.3 The Weaver's Pledge — In-Game Codex

The opening text, read in the voice of the Heartstone, upon first awakening:
"Little thread, you are not the first to weave, but you may be the last. The Loom is broken, but the shuttle is still in your hand. Run, build, love the Spindlekin, and remember: every stitch is a choice against the void. You are never alone. I am with you, in every thread of light. Weave well."

This text is inscribed on the first page of your Pattern Book, and its ink is made of Lumen dust that gently glows in the dark.

